# Merge drivers for frida-sweep / ghidra-sweep append-only files.
#
# These four files are touched by EVERY parallel-fanout worker branch and
# conflict predictably at sweep time. The conflict pattern is always
# "union of additions" (each branch adds dict entries / log lines / build
# entries near the end of the file). `merge=union` is git's built-in
# driver that keeps both sides without conflict markers — equivalent to
# the manual mechanical resolution the frida-sweep skill describes.
#
# Caveat: union merges naively concatenate conflicting hunks. For these
# four files that's exactly right because each branch ADDS in different
# regions. If two branches ever modify the SAME line (e.g. rename an
# existing entry), union will duplicate it — surface the resulting
# syntactic issue in build / re-classify and resolve by hand.
#
# These do NOT apply to merges from main into a worktree (which never
# conflict in the first place). They apply at the frida-sweep `git merge`
# step where worker branches converge.

mashedmod/build.bat              merge=union
re/analysis/CHANGELOG.md         merge=union
re/PROMOTION_QUEUE.md            merge=union

# hooks.csv is per-row data with strict format. Auto-union is too risky
# (could produce duplicate-RVA rows or torn rows). Keep manual resolution.
#
# re/frida/hooks_registry.py was REMOVED from the union set 2026-05-26 after
# the c3_batch_t sweep: it is a multi-line nested-dict structure, and when
# worker branches inherit a shared baseline (all branched from the same main),
# union splices new dict entries INTO the middle of inherited entries — every
# splice truncated an entry body and broke Python syntax (4 manual repairs
# needed that sweep). build.bat / CHANGELOG.md / PROMOTION_QUEUE.md stay on
# union because their entries are single self-contained lines. hooks_registry.py
# now uses default 3-way merge — conflicts there get hand-resolved (keep both
# dict entries, one closing brace), same as hooks.csv.
